\section{Analysis \& Results}\label{sec:MEC_results}




\subsection{Radiative Versus Magnetic Energy}\label{sec:RadVsMag_TypWay}

In Figure~\ref{fig:FvsPhi} we provide plots of radiative (covering all AIA passbands, with exception of 4500\,{\AA}) versus magnetic fluxes (from HMI observations) with respect to our feature set.






Directly comparing Figure~\ref{fig:FvsPhi}'s upper coronal results (i.e., 94\,{\AA}) to Figure 5b of \cite{Benevolenskayaetal2002ApJ} reveals distinctive similarities. Particularly, our results alignment with the suggestions of \citet{Benevolenskayaetal2002ApJ,FludraIreland2003AA} for two

differing dependencies of radiative energy versus that of the underlying magnetic field. However, as one progresses to cooler atmospheric layers, i.e., the TR to the chromosphere (171\,{\AA} and 304\,{\AA}, respectively), our Figure~\ref{fig:FvsPhi} results are more consistent with notions of a single linear correlation of radiative to magnetic energy in the solar atmosphere (i.e., \citealt{Pevtsovetal2003ApJ}).


Though not shown, 4500\,{\AA} observations compared to that of the underlying magnetic field provide no evidence for thermal to magnetic energy coupling. That is little to negligible variations in its radiative energy occurs for increasing magnetic field strengths, independent of feature. CHs were possibly an exception, as decreasing radiative energies were witnessed. However, such instances were not typical of its CH results in general.

In relation to the results of Figure~\ref{fig:FvsPhi}, they reveal as a function of our analyzed features and for solar atmospheric temperatures of $\log T$\,$<$\,4.8 (i.e., 1700\,{\AA} and 1600\,{\AA} plots therein), minimal radiative energy distinctions\ exist. However, the presence of a slight ``ankle,"

at approximately $\log B$\,$\sim$\,1.0 where a blending of the radiative energies observed in CH, QS, AR, ARC (to a lesser degree), and FD occurs. We point out such results are expected considering the higher plasma beta (i.e., $\beta$; ratio of gas to magnetic pressure), conditions that should prevail here. In contrast, the ARC results of these regimes are trending towards the believed linear thermal to magnetic energy relationship (e.g., \citealt{Pevtsovetal2003ApJ}). Relative to other gross features

enhanced ARC photospheric magnetic energies could be leading to frozen-in-flux conditions (i.e., $\beta$\,$<$\,1) at cooler atmospheric layers/heights.


In the chromosphere, i.e., 304\,{\AA}, results are consistent with the expectations of a linear radiative to magnetic energy trend, and shows it scales across the gross

feature classes. These results reveal an emerging distinction between observed radiances of CH and QS conditions, which correlate with similar strengths in their underlying magnetic field energies. Note the

ankle identified in cooler passbands remains distinctly discernable in chromospheric emission.


In passbands dominated by emission from upper TR temperatures (i.e., 131\,{\AA} and 171\,{\AA} passbands), with the possibility of lower and/or upper coronal contributions (i.e., 131\,{\AA}; \citealt{ODwyeretal2010AA,DelZannaetal2011AA,Schmelzetal2013SoPh,Boerneretal2014SoPh}), the ankle

structure of cooler atmospheric layers has ``smoothed" out. However TR radiative versus magnetic energy distributions give rise to signatures of an knee and ankle.

The knee corresponding to CH conditions that is distributed downward to lower radiative energies than other studied feature classes; observations consistent with suggestions of \cite{Pevtsovetal2003ApJ} for regions dominated by single polarity magnetic fluxes. The ankle, emerging where a portion of ARC observations have ``migrated" to higher energies, compared to their AR counterparts.

In the middle corona, described here by AIA's 193\,{\AA} and 211\,{\AA} passbands (6.2\,$\lesssim$\,$\log T$\,$\lesssim$\,6.3; Figure~\ref{fig:FvsPhi}), results are generally similar to those of the TR. The only distinction of coronal to TR exists in a comparison of their CH and QS radiative energy distributions. Both are characterized by decreased radiative energy distributions relative to other analyzed features. The ``upper TR -- coronal" ARC ankle suggest the possibility of heating not direct attributable to the magnetic field. Notions that algin with recent challenges to the standard coronal heating model interpretation \citep{Parker1983GApFD}. Particularly, observations of inversely proportional emission measure (EM) to underlying field strengths of ARCs

\citep{Warrenetal2012ApJ}, as well as the absence of non-thermal velocity to temperature trends \citep{BrooksWarren2015arXiv}.













































At hotter coronal temperatures, i.e., those of 335\,{\AA} and 94\,{\AA} observations, similar characteristics prevail to that of the middle corona, and to lesser degree the TR. In opposition to cooler regions, however, at upper coronal regimes the upper ARC ankle appears smoother. Thereby, resulting in a distinctive linear relation of QS, FD-R, AR, and ARC features, listed in accordance with increasing magnetic field strengths of the respective distributions.


